WEBVTT

00:05.005 --> 00:07.966
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

00:07.966 --> 00:09.968
<i>♪ ♪</i>

00:09.968 --> 00:13.013
<i>[tense music]</i>

00:13.013 --> 00:15.557
<i>- My name's Jason Nass.</i>

00:15.557 --> 00:17.267
<i>I'm 45 years old.</i>

00:17.267 --> 00:19.686
I am here to win $10,000

00:19.686 --> 00:21.897
<i>and a championship title.</i>

00:21.897 --> 00:24.858
<i>The money's gonna help get</i>
<i>my fiancée and I into a house</i>

00:24.858 --> 00:28.237
and no longer live
in the heart of the city.

00:28.237 --> 00:30.781
<i>- My name is</i>
<i>Daniel James Reichow.</i>

00:30.781 --> 00:32.407
<i>And I run Drifters Forge.</i>

00:32.407 --> 00:35.536
I've lived in probably
a 150 different towns.

00:35.536 --> 00:37.037
<i>I've been in the military.</i>

00:37.037 --> 00:39.873
I'm just a good old
down-home boy.

00:39.873 --> 00:41.708
<i>- My name is Drew Goodson.</i>

00:41.708 --> 00:43.502
I'm 18 years old,
and I study

00:43.502 --> 00:45.295
mechanical engineering
at Louisiana Tech.

00:45.295 --> 00:48.215
<i>I've noticed that Doug</i>
<i>likes recurved blades.</i>

00:48.215 --> 00:50.092
I don't know if that's
how he likes his women,

00:50.092 --> 00:53.387
curvy, but my grandmother has
totally got a crush on him

00:53.387 --> 00:56.014
especially when he says,
"It will kill."

00:56.014 --> 00:57.683
<i>- My name is Larry Metcalf.</i>

00:57.683 --> 00:59.768
I do what we call old-school.

00:59.768 --> 01:02.312
<i>We've been blacksmithing</i>
<i>for over 5,000 years.</i>

01:02.312 --> 01:04.106
Why not do it
the way they did it?

01:04.106 --> 01:06.567
<i>I might be 61 years old,</i>
<i>but you know what?</i>

01:06.567 --> 01:08.277
Old age and treachery
will overcome

01:08.277 --> 01:11.488
youth and skill
every time.

01:11.488 --> 01:14.449
- Bladesmiths,
welcome to The Forge.

01:14.449 --> 01:16.868
You're here to
compete for the title

01:16.868 --> 01:19.079
of "Forged in Fire" champion
in three timed rounds

01:19.079 --> 01:20.747
of edged weapon-making
competition,

01:20.747 --> 01:24.001
specifically designed
to put every aspect

01:24.001 --> 01:25.961
of your skills to the test,

01:25.961 --> 01:28.088
all in front of our panel
of expert judges,

01:28.088 --> 01:29.381
so let's meet them now.

01:29.381 --> 01:32.384
ABS Master Smith, J. Neilson.

01:32.384 --> 01:35.512
Historic weapons recreation
specialist, David Baker.

01:35.512 --> 01:38.890
Edged-weapon specialist,
Doug Marcaida.

01:38.890 --> 01:41.226
Bladesmiths, it's one thing
to ask for blades

01:41.226 --> 01:43.854
in a signature style,
however,

01:43.854 --> 01:45.355
in today's first round
of competition

01:45.355 --> 01:47.941
we won't be doing
any signature styles.

01:47.941 --> 01:50.027
Instead, we'll be making

01:50.027 --> 01:52.279
one of J. Neilson's
favorite weapons.

01:52.279 --> 01:54.614
That weapon is...

01:54.614 --> 01:56.616
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

01:56.616 --> 01:58.869
The European dagger.

01:58.869 --> 02:01.038
- I have actually
never made a dagger.

02:01.038 --> 02:03.081
It's not something
I really wanna do,

02:03.081 --> 02:05.959
but I guess I'm doing it now.

02:05.959 --> 02:07.502
- Gentlemen,
your blades must fall

02:07.502 --> 02:08.670
<i>within the</i>
<i>following parameters.</i>

02:08.670 --> 02:10.255
<i>The length of the blade</i>

02:10.255 --> 02:11.965
<i>must fall between</i>
<i>10 and 12 inches.</i>

02:11.965 --> 02:13.842
<i>The width of the blade</i>
<i>at its widest point</i>

02:13.842 --> 02:16.261
<i>must be at least</i>
<i>1 1/4 inches.</i>

02:16.261 --> 02:18.972
And you must have
a double-edged blade

02:18.972 --> 02:20.682
with a ricasso that is at least

02:20.682 --> 02:23.894
3/4 of an inch long.

02:23.894 --> 02:26.313
But there is one more thing
that we need to discuss

02:26.313 --> 02:28.398
and that's metal.

02:28.398 --> 02:30.484
Today, you'll be using this.

02:30.484 --> 02:33.528
<i>♪ ♪</i>

02:33.528 --> 02:35.364
Damascus steel.

02:35.364 --> 02:38.867
You'll have to combine
two or more of these steels

02:38.867 --> 02:42.537
into a billet of Damascus from
which to forge your dagger.

02:42.537 --> 02:45.415
<i>- Come on, Damascus.</i>

02:45.415 --> 02:47.793
<i>This was the one thing</i>
<i>I really didn't wanna see.</i>

02:47.793 --> 02:50.837
- Because this is
J. Neilson's favorite weapon,

02:50.837 --> 02:52.673
he's got some advice.

02:52.673 --> 02:54.216
- There's a lot of ways
you could screw it up.

02:54.216 --> 02:55.884
Try not to do that.

02:55.884 --> 02:57.803
I'm gonna come down
and visit each of you

02:57.803 --> 03:00.222
during the forging process
in this challenge,

03:00.222 --> 03:01.348
try to help you out.

03:01.348 --> 03:02.849
<i>- I think all of us can</i>

03:02.849 --> 03:05.268
learn something
from J.'s advice.

03:05.268 --> 03:07.270
I got my nervous jitters on,

03:07.270 --> 03:09.356
but I'm ready, let's do this.

03:09.356 --> 03:11.149
<i>♪ ♪</i>

03:11.149 --> 03:12.901
- Keep in mind that
in the second round,

03:12.901 --> 03:14.569
you'll be attaching
handles to those blades,

03:14.569 --> 03:16.446
turning them into
fully functional weapons

03:16.446 --> 03:19.032
that will be tested for
strength and durability

03:19.032 --> 03:22.411
in a fuel can stab
and for edge retention

03:22.411 --> 03:24.329
in a fish slice.

03:24.329 --> 03:27.207
You'll have three hours in
which to complete your work.

03:27.207 --> 03:29.584
Failure to meet a single
one of our parameters

03:29.584 --> 03:32.087
is grounds for immediate
dismissal from this forge.

03:32.087 --> 03:33.713
Good luck, bladesmiths,

03:33.713 --> 03:35.966
your three hours starts now.

03:35.966 --> 03:37.926
<i>[rock music]</i>

03:37.926 --> 03:41.596
Okay, so we've got 52
100 ball bearings;

03:41.596 --> 03:45.517
we got chain saw, springs,
powdered steel, you name it--

03:45.517 --> 03:47.894
everything out there
can be turned into a knife.

03:47.894 --> 03:49.813
<i>- You could do</i>
<i>a canister upright,</i>

03:49.813 --> 03:51.565
<i>canoe, cube.</i>

03:51.565 --> 03:53.066
<i>You could do laminate,</i>
<i>layer it up,</i>

03:53.066 --> 03:54.651
<i>do multiple</i>
<i>different patterns.</i>

03:54.651 --> 03:58.071
There is a possibility
of thousands of patterns

03:58.071 --> 04:01.158
and designs right there
on that one table.

04:01.158 --> 04:03.452
<i>- So, I've got make</i>
<i>J. Neilson's favorite blade,</i>

04:03.452 --> 04:05.912
but it also has to be my blade.

04:05.912 --> 04:07.164
[device cranking]

04:07.164 --> 04:08.707
<i>I'm thinking layered steel</i>

04:08.707 --> 04:10.292
<i>because it's not</i>
<i>really tough to weld.</i>

04:10.292 --> 04:11.960
<i>It's really easy to draw out.</i>

04:11.960 --> 04:14.546
There's a less of
a chance of it failing.

04:14.546 --> 04:17.007
I immediately start
to clean off the steel

04:17.007 --> 04:18.592
'cause they've got
iron oxide on them.

04:18.592 --> 04:20.135
It's really bad for a weld,

04:20.135 --> 04:22.637
it's just evil
for a bladesmith.

04:22.637 --> 04:24.222
- Taking that few
extra minutes

04:24.222 --> 04:27.559
to clean up that steel
is just a smart move.

04:27.559 --> 04:29.144
<i>♪ ♪</i>

04:29.144 --> 04:30.604
- Oh, my God.

04:30.604 --> 04:32.647
- Can I get a Band-Aid?

04:32.647 --> 04:36.485
<i>I ran my thumb</i>
<i>across a 36 grit belt,</i>

04:36.485 --> 04:38.111
<i>and it ripped the</i>
<i>tip of my thumb off</i>

04:38.111 --> 04:39.821
and left it
flapping in the wind.

04:39.821 --> 04:41.948
I'm off to a wonderful start.

04:41.948 --> 04:43.825
- Less than three minutes,
one of our contestants

04:43.825 --> 04:45.494
is already
bleeding on the floor.

04:45.494 --> 04:46.912
- Yeah, that's a record.

04:46.912 --> 04:48.663
- That hurt.

04:48.663 --> 04:50.373
- What do you think is
the most difficult part

04:50.373 --> 04:51.625
of making a dagger?

04:51.625 --> 04:53.126
- Biggest thing is you gotta

04:53.126 --> 04:55.295
balance function and art.

04:55.295 --> 04:58.507
What you want in a dagger
is a mirror image.

04:58.507 --> 05:00.425
You wanna have one side done

05:00.425 --> 05:02.010
and then you wanna
mirror the other side.

05:02.010 --> 05:03.887
- Okay.

05:03.887 --> 05:05.639
<i>- And this is one of the</i>
<i>knives that is required</i>

05:05.639 --> 05:07.599
<i>to become an ABS Master Smith.</i>

05:07.599 --> 05:09.309
<i>So that right there</i>
<i>tells you something.</i>

05:09.309 --> 05:11.394
- Flux the hell out of it.

05:11.394 --> 05:12.771
- The more flux
you put on there,

05:12.771 --> 05:14.648
the more of a mess
you're gonna make,

05:14.648 --> 05:16.316
which is more of a mess
you gotta deal with later.

05:16.316 --> 05:17.943
- You're saying you shouldn't
give a lot of flux.

05:17.943 --> 05:19.277
- I don't get a lot of flux.
- To use it.

05:19.277 --> 05:20.445
- You don't wanna
flux things up.

05:20.445 --> 05:22.405
- I don't really give a flux.

05:22.405 --> 05:25.867
<i>- Damascus steel is</i>
<i>a time-consuming thing.</i>

05:25.867 --> 05:28.995
We have three hours
to make these blades.

05:28.995 --> 05:30.539
Three hours.

05:30.539 --> 05:32.791
Yeah, ah, you.

05:32.791 --> 05:36.336
My game plan is build
a laminated billet.

05:36.336 --> 05:39.256
Simple, functional,
and hopefully,

05:39.256 --> 05:41.216
if I give a little bit
and pull it off,

05:41.216 --> 05:43.134
a little bit
of elegance as well.

05:43.134 --> 05:46.137
<i>Knowing this is one</i>
<i>of J.'s favorite weapons,</i>

05:46.137 --> 05:49.015
I certainly wanna do something
that I can be proud of

05:49.015 --> 05:51.476
and he thinks is
at least halfway decent.

05:51.476 --> 05:53.436
<i>♪ ♪</i>

05:53.436 --> 05:55.939
- Ah, where's the--right there.

05:55.939 --> 05:58.316
<i>Doing Damascus</i>
<i>steel layering--</i>

05:58.316 --> 06:00.569
what I would like to do,
if I got time,

06:00.569 --> 06:02.946
would be actually throw
a fold in there also

06:02.946 --> 06:05.282
<i>so I get a little bit</i>
<i>more layers into it.</i>

06:05.282 --> 06:07.117
There's three different
steels in there.

06:07.117 --> 06:09.160
I just kinda interlaced
the layers on it.

06:09.160 --> 06:10.745
We'll see when it comes out.

06:10.745 --> 06:14.040
Mystery meat!

06:14.040 --> 06:15.834
- I'm gonna just go
for a stack billet.

06:15.834 --> 06:17.586
[machine whirring]

06:17.586 --> 06:19.296
<i>I'm thinking I wanna</i>
<i>get a fold in there</i>

06:19.296 --> 06:22.132
<i>and also do kind of</i>
<i>like a ladder pattern</i>

06:22.132 --> 06:24.050
to go down the
point of the blade.

06:24.050 --> 06:26.094
[dramatic thud]

06:26.094 --> 06:28.346
<i>I've never made</i>
<i>a dagger before,</i>

06:28.346 --> 06:30.265
so I'm gonna just wing it,
see how it goes from there.

06:30.265 --> 06:31.725
[hammering]

06:31.725 --> 06:33.435
- Bladesmiths, you have only

06:33.435 --> 06:35.103
two hours remaining
to finish your work.

06:35.103 --> 06:36.730
- Hot steel.

06:36.730 --> 06:38.899
- Everybody's
layering up the steel.

06:38.899 --> 06:41.651
- Smart move.
- Go the easy route.

06:41.651 --> 06:43.320
- David Baker--

06:43.320 --> 06:44.738
I feel like I look
like him today

06:44.738 --> 06:46.364
with the vest and a tie.

06:46.364 --> 06:48.450
- Is Drew underdressed
for this?

06:48.450 --> 06:50.827
- No, no, I think
Drew's dialed it in, actually.

06:50.827 --> 06:52.454
- [chuckle]

06:52.454 --> 06:53.788
<i>- I've got to</i>
<i>make this unique.</i>

06:53.788 --> 06:55.999
First thing is ladder pattern.

06:55.999 --> 06:58.335
<i>This won't do anything to the</i>
<i>functionality of the blade,</i>

06:58.335 --> 07:00.629
but it'll make my blade
look different.

07:00.629 --> 07:02.631
- If Drew's gonna be
doing a ladder pattern,

07:02.631 --> 07:04.257
piece of steel that thick--

07:04.257 --> 07:05.842
he needs to cut those
grooves in a lot deeper.

07:05.842 --> 07:08.053
[hammering]

07:08.053 --> 07:09.971
I'm gonna go talk to Drew for
a minute about his patterning.

07:09.971 --> 07:11.598
- Go for it.

07:11.598 --> 07:14.017
- Hey, Drew.
- Hey.

07:14.017 --> 07:15.101
- Talk to me about
what you're doing

07:15.101 --> 07:16.561
with your patterning here.

07:16.561 --> 07:18.229
- I don't think
it's deep enough.

07:18.229 --> 07:19.648
- That's my concern.

07:19.648 --> 07:21.608
You've got a large billet
there still.

07:21.608 --> 07:23.860
You didn't grind in
very deep,

07:23.860 --> 07:25.904
so if you're gonna try
and pattern that out,

07:25.904 --> 07:27.656
your pattern's probably
not gonna show up.

07:27.656 --> 07:30.742
- Yeah, I might fold it over
again to get some more layers.

07:30.742 --> 07:32.494
- That would be nice to see.

07:32.494 --> 07:34.037
You don't wanna put the
work into that pattern

07:34.037 --> 07:35.497
and have it disappear
once you forge it out.

07:35.497 --> 07:37.165
- I'm not a fool.

07:37.165 --> 07:38.958
I've seen people lose because

07:38.958 --> 07:40.710
<i>they don't take advice</i>
<i>from the judges,</i>

07:40.710 --> 07:42.754
and I'm gonna take
every single bit I can get.

07:42.754 --> 07:44.547
All right.

07:44.547 --> 07:46.132
- Not good.

07:46.132 --> 07:48.426
Not good, didn't stick.

07:48.426 --> 07:50.553
- Larry's having a lot
of trouble with his steel.

07:50.553 --> 07:52.847
- His steel's not
coming together.

07:52.847 --> 07:55.183
- Not friggin' good.

07:55.183 --> 07:56.851
I couldn't get
this thing to weld

07:56.851 --> 07:58.978
if my life depended upon it.

07:58.978 --> 08:00.438
- Is it not sticking at all?

08:00.438 --> 08:02.148
- No, it's not sticking at all.

08:02.148 --> 08:04.192
I thought I had it
pretty clean there.

08:04.192 --> 08:05.568
- You might wanna open it up

08:05.568 --> 08:07.153
and take a grinding
wheel to it,

08:07.153 --> 08:08.655
just try and straighten
everything out,

08:08.655 --> 08:10.156
'cause once it's
not sticking now,

08:10.156 --> 08:12.117
it's not going to.
- Yeah, I know.

08:12.117 --> 08:13.743
- We've been talking about this
again and again and again.

08:13.743 --> 08:15.870
He didn't clean it,
he didn't grind that inside.

08:15.870 --> 08:18.915
<i>[rock music]</i>

08:18.915 --> 08:20.625
- Hot stuff, guys.

08:20.625 --> 08:23.670
Back in for some heat up.

08:23.670 --> 08:26.423
Come on, stick.

08:26.423 --> 08:29.217
<i>I think he gave me</i>
<i>some sound advice,</i>

08:29.217 --> 08:31.302
<i>and he's done this</i>
<i>a lot longer than I have,</i>

08:31.302 --> 08:34.013
so I gotta try it
and see what happens.

08:34.013 --> 08:36.141
Damn it, come on, really?

08:36.141 --> 08:38.476
Dead and weld, coming out guys.

08:38.476 --> 08:39.477
It's just, it didn't work.

08:39.477 --> 08:40.937
Hot stuff.

08:40.937 --> 08:42.856
<i>And that's my fault completely</i>

08:42.856 --> 08:45.191
because I didn't clean my steel
when I started on it.

08:45.191 --> 08:47.152
<i>♪ ♪</i>

08:47.152 --> 08:48.820
<i>I don't have time</i>
<i>to be messing around</i>

08:48.820 --> 08:51.197
with this folding and
trying to reweld all this.

08:51.197 --> 08:52.866
<i>I would've loved</i>
<i>to have folded it,</i>

08:52.866 --> 08:54.701
but I just went
with a single layer.

08:54.701 --> 08:57.245
- His pattern's
not gonna show up.

08:57.245 --> 09:01.583
<i>♪ ♪</i>

09:01.583 --> 09:04.169
- I'm gonna have to pull
it apart and clean it.

09:04.169 --> 09:06.046
- Aww, man.
- 'Cause that ain't sticking.

09:06.046 --> 09:07.881
- Man.
- Daniel's steel also

09:07.881 --> 09:09.507
isn't forging--
forge welding.

09:09.507 --> 09:11.634
See, it's opened up.

09:11.634 --> 09:13.470
- Daniel, I take you're having
problems with things sticking.

09:13.470 --> 09:14.763
What's going on?

09:14.763 --> 09:16.848
- We'll see if it
sticks this time.

09:16.848 --> 09:18.516
If it's not, I'm gonna cut it
off, I got plenty of material.

09:18.516 --> 09:20.935
- You can clean it up and
cut it into smaller pieces

09:20.935 --> 09:22.562
and do a short stack,
that way you have

09:22.562 --> 09:24.564
less surface area
to try and forge weld,

09:24.564 --> 09:25.940
but make sure you get
everything cleaned up

09:25.940 --> 09:27.525
between those layers

09:27.525 --> 09:28.818
and it'll stick better
with the right heat.

09:28.818 --> 09:30.070
All right?

09:30.070 --> 09:32.113
<i>♪ ♪</i>

09:32.113 --> 09:34.115
<i>This is J.'s favorite weapon,</i>

09:34.115 --> 09:36.451
so I'll use any advice
that I can get.

09:36.451 --> 09:38.745
<i>♪ ♪</i>

09:38.745 --> 09:40.622
Feels like time is ticking by.

09:40.622 --> 09:42.791
<i>I am rushing so hard,</i>

09:42.791 --> 09:44.417
<i>and I don't wanna</i>
<i>take the time</i>

09:44.417 --> 09:46.044
<i>to remake a whole</i>
<i>'nother billet.</i>

09:46.044 --> 09:48.213
Nope, ain't sticking.

09:48.213 --> 09:50.340
I'm cutting it.

09:50.340 --> 09:53.176
<i>My plan is now</i>
<i>to cut off the fold,</i>

09:53.176 --> 09:55.929
<i>try to stretch the metal out,</i>
<i>and meet the parameters.</i>

09:55.929 --> 09:58.723
<i>I hope I have enough</i>
<i>metal left for this.</i>

09:58.723 --> 10:00.892
<i>♪ ♪</i>

10:00.892 --> 10:02.227
- Generally, in the forge,

10:02.227 --> 10:04.854
I am a very happy,
upbeat guy.

10:04.854 --> 10:08.191
Big, nice, wide tang.

10:08.191 --> 10:10.318
I know I talk to myself a lot.

10:10.318 --> 10:12.362
We're gonna go to the hammer.

10:12.362 --> 10:15.615
Usually isn't a problem until
I start answering myself,

10:15.615 --> 10:18.785
which strangely does
occasionally happen.

10:18.785 --> 10:20.620
Meh.

10:20.620 --> 10:22.163
I'll be okay.

10:22.163 --> 10:24.249
- Jason is really
moving right along.

10:24.249 --> 10:26.167
He looks like he
hasn't had any problems

10:26.167 --> 10:27.919
getting his steel to stick.

10:27.919 --> 10:31.005
He's hammering bevels
into his dagger right now,

10:31.005 --> 10:32.549
so that's nice to see.

10:32.549 --> 10:34.092
- Yeah, Jason's been
chugging right along.

10:34.092 --> 10:35.260
He's been doing a great job.

10:35.260 --> 10:37.303
<i>- My profile's set,</i>

10:37.303 --> 10:38.847
I've got my tang in there,

10:38.847 --> 10:40.682
<i>I know where my</i>
<i>ricasso's gonna be.</i>

10:40.682 --> 10:42.433
It's time to hit the grinder.

10:42.433 --> 10:44.435
<i>♪ ♪</i>

10:44.435 --> 10:46.604
- Bladesmiths!

10:46.604 --> 10:49.566
Two hours has elapsed!

10:49.566 --> 10:51.568
- Damn, am I the
last one in a forge?

10:51.568 --> 10:53.278
I guess so.

10:53.278 --> 10:55.363
I'm feeling like
I'm way behind.

10:55.363 --> 10:56.698
You're behind the
8 ball here, Larry,

10:56.698 --> 10:57.991
You gotta get moving here.

10:57.991 --> 11:00.743
Coming out hot.

11:00.743 --> 11:02.245
<i>♪ ♪</i>

11:02.245 --> 11:03.913
- Oh, my God.

11:03.913 --> 11:08.084
Look at Larry's mangled
mess of metal over there.

11:08.084 --> 11:10.003
- Got a little overzealous.

11:10.003 --> 11:12.505
It kinda crushed it a little
bit on the tang on me.

11:12.505 --> 11:15.425
Now, just not cutting it.

11:15.425 --> 11:17.552
I don't have time to redo this.

11:17.552 --> 11:19.846
<i>Now I gotta figure out</i>
<i>how I'm gonna fix this.</i>

11:19.846 --> 11:22.473
- Man, Larry's in a bad spot.

11:22.473 --> 11:25.493
- Larry might wanna
think about starting over.

11:28.771 --> 11:30.899
- Think he was
squeezing in a tang,

11:30.899 --> 11:33.776
but the problem is that
steel was already so thin,

11:33.776 --> 11:35.653
that as you
squeeze the tang in,

11:35.653 --> 11:37.864
he kinda rolled it
in on itself.

11:37.864 --> 11:39.866
- It's not gonna work,
not gonna work.

11:39.866 --> 11:41.576
I have to cut this
piece of steel off.

11:41.576 --> 11:43.453
Sparky.

11:43.453 --> 11:45.663
The only thing that
I have concerns about

11:45.663 --> 11:48.541
is I hope I got enough meat
left to make this tang.

11:48.541 --> 11:50.460
Oh yeah...
[mutters indistinctly]

11:50.460 --> 11:53.421
<i>[rock music]</i>

11:53.421 --> 11:57.342
<i>♪ ♪</i>

11:57.342 --> 11:58.927
- I think it'll do.

11:58.927 --> 12:01.512
- We just had
Drew quench his blade.

12:01.512 --> 12:02.889
- Quench early.
- Yup.

12:02.889 --> 12:04.057
- Doesn't hurt the blade,

12:04.057 --> 12:05.391
you can grind a quenched blade.

12:05.391 --> 12:07.352
- Yup.

12:07.352 --> 12:08.937
<i>- Grinding the blade,</i>

12:08.937 --> 12:10.647
<i>especially for a European</i>
<i>dagger,</i>

12:10.647 --> 12:11.689
it's very important
because you gotta

12:11.689 --> 12:14.067
get everything straight.

12:14.067 --> 12:16.486
I'm spending a
ton of time on this,

12:16.486 --> 12:18.905
and I think it's time
well worth spent.

12:18.905 --> 12:22.700
<i>♪ ♪</i>

12:22.700 --> 12:25.161
- Look how thin that blade is,

12:25.161 --> 12:26.996
and he hasn't even
quenched it yet.

12:26.996 --> 12:29.958
- Seeing the grinding
that Daniel is doing

12:29.958 --> 12:31.125
and the way his blade looks,

12:31.125 --> 12:33.253
he might see a good warp
come up.

12:33.253 --> 12:34.629
- I'm very nervous.

12:34.629 --> 12:36.381
<i>I did not wanna take the time</i>

12:36.381 --> 12:38.341
<i>to take J.'s advice.</i>

12:38.341 --> 12:40.468
I should've cleaned
this billet off.

12:40.468 --> 12:42.220
I could've cut it up
into little pieces

12:42.220 --> 12:43.763
like J. had suggested,

12:43.763 --> 12:46.140
but I have got to
get it heat-treated,

12:46.140 --> 12:49.102
<i>♪ ♪</i>

12:49.102 --> 12:51.271
- Daniel's just
quenched his dagger.

12:51.271 --> 12:53.398
Take a look at it.

12:53.398 --> 12:55.650
I could see the warp from here.
- Can you?

12:55.650 --> 12:56.985
- Yeah.
- Oh, boy.

12:56.985 --> 12:58.194
<i>- And this sucks.</i>

12:58.194 --> 13:00.863
I have a warp right in my tang.

13:00.863 --> 13:02.615
<i>My tang's already thin,</i>

13:02.615 --> 13:04.242
<i>my blade's already thin,</i>

13:04.242 --> 13:05.702
[stammers]
I've gotta take more out of it.

13:05.702 --> 13:07.662
This concerns me greatly.

13:07.662 --> 13:10.581
<i>[rock music]</i>

13:10.581 --> 13:13.167
- I'm gonna need to start
quenching here soon.

13:13.167 --> 13:15.670
Definitely want
a normalizing cycle

13:15.670 --> 13:17.422
or two if I can get it.

13:17.422 --> 13:19.382
- Jason, tip first.

13:19.382 --> 13:21.884
- Yeah, I'm gonna go over
and rip his hair out.

13:21.884 --> 13:23.511
Hey, Jason.

13:23.511 --> 13:24.637
- Yeah?
- What you got going there?

13:24.637 --> 13:26.222
Let me see the blade.

13:26.222 --> 13:28.850
- I like how J. prefaces
the tutorial moment with,

13:28.850 --> 13:30.727
"I'm about to rip
that guy's hair out."

13:30.727 --> 13:31.686
- [laughter]
- I'ma go talk to him.

13:31.686 --> 13:33.146
[all chuckling]

13:33.146 --> 13:35.148
- Okay, you see right there?
- Yup.

13:35.148 --> 13:37.567
- That's the thinnest part
of your steel right there,

13:37.567 --> 13:38.693
That's gonna heat
up the quickest.

13:38.693 --> 13:40.278
- Right.

13:40.278 --> 13:41.696
- When you're
thermal cycling a blade,

13:41.696 --> 13:42.739
it's very easy,
especially with a dagger,

13:42.739 --> 13:44.615
to overheat the point.

13:44.615 --> 13:46.576
And then you're kind of
working at counter purposes.

13:46.576 --> 13:48.870
Instead of shrinking the grain,
you're really expanding it.

13:48.870 --> 13:50.455
- Right.

13:50.455 --> 13:51.748
- You might wanna
flip that around.

13:51.748 --> 13:53.750
Heat up the mass
of your blade first,

13:53.750 --> 13:55.209
and then flip it around,

13:55.209 --> 13:56.502
yeah, just watch that tip, man.

13:56.502 --> 13:57.920
- Thank you.

13:57.920 --> 14:00.131
My attention slipped
for a moment and

14:00.131 --> 14:02.091
he really saved my butt there.

14:02.091 --> 14:04.135
- So, right here,
you can really see,

14:04.135 --> 14:05.887
like, there you go, he's--

14:05.887 --> 14:07.513
Jason's flipping his
blade around right now,

14:07.513 --> 14:08.723
and you can see that
tip's just not as hot.

14:08.723 --> 14:10.058
- Yup.

14:10.058 --> 14:11.225
- That entire
blade's heated up.

14:11.225 --> 14:12.143
- There we go
- There he goes.

14:12.143 --> 14:13.644
He's in.

14:13.644 --> 14:15.396
<i>♪ ♪</i>

14:15.396 --> 14:17.273
- There goes the
rest of his hair.

14:17.273 --> 14:19.692
<i>♪ ♪</i>

14:19.692 --> 14:22.111
- Jason looks happy.

14:22.111 --> 14:24.197
- Drew's over
at the acid right now

14:24.197 --> 14:25.865
trying to get the acid open.
- Trying.

14:25.865 --> 14:27.784
- He could swing a hammer
for three hours,

14:27.784 --> 14:29.410
but he can't get
the cap off the acid.

14:29.410 --> 14:30.912
- If you had hair on your
chest, you could do that.

14:30.912 --> 14:32.497
- [chuckles]

14:32.497 --> 14:34.457
- He got it, he got it.

14:34.457 --> 14:35.833
<i>- So I'm just gonna check</i>
<i>the pattern real quick</i>

14:35.833 --> 14:37.085
and see what I'm working with,

14:37.085 --> 14:38.211
see if the judges
are gonna like it.

14:38.211 --> 14:40.213
Oh, my God.

14:40.213 --> 14:41.964
<i>This pattern looks amazing.</i>

14:41.964 --> 14:43.549
It's poppin'.

14:43.549 --> 14:44.842
[sheepish laugh]

14:44.842 --> 14:47.929
- Five, four, three,

14:47.929 --> 14:49.931
two, one.

14:49.931 --> 14:51.349
Drop your tools,
shut down your machines,

14:51.349 --> 14:53.392
this round is over.

14:53.392 --> 14:55.520
<i>- Obviously, this is the</i>
<i>best dagger I've ever made,</i>

14:55.520 --> 14:57.230
since it's the only one.

14:57.230 --> 14:59.315
<i>My only concerns are</i>

14:59.315 --> 15:02.443
<i>how thin my blade</i>
<i>and my tang are.</i>

15:02.443 --> 15:03.903
- All right, bladesmiths,

15:03.903 --> 15:05.363
over the last three hours,

15:05.363 --> 15:06.864
you worked on
your European daggers.

15:06.864 --> 15:09.867
Let's see if your
blades are up to specs.

15:09.867 --> 15:11.786
Jason, you're up first.

15:11.786 --> 15:13.788
<i>[tense music]</i>

15:13.788 --> 15:15.123
<i>- Well, first off,</i>
<i>your steel looks really good.</i>

15:15.123 --> 15:16.833
It's nice and clean.

15:16.833 --> 15:18.126
Love to see a lot of
that material taken out

15:18.126 --> 15:19.794
maybe just a taper
put into this.

15:19.794 --> 15:21.712
<i>Ricasso is good.</i>
<i>Nicely done.</i>

15:21.712 --> 15:23.256
- Thank you.

15:23.256 --> 15:24.423
- Jason, I like what
you got going on here.

15:24.423 --> 15:27.093
You've got a lot
of meat in here,

15:27.093 --> 15:29.679
which is a good thing 'cause
if you look down your blade,

15:29.679 --> 15:31.472
you've got a twist
to that blade.

15:31.472 --> 15:33.724
But you still got
enough meat on here

15:33.724 --> 15:34.976
that you can
actually grind that

15:34.976 --> 15:36.561
and correct that
twist in there.

15:36.561 --> 15:38.020
Overall, came out really nice.

15:38.020 --> 15:39.105
- Thank you.

15:39.105 --> 15:40.439
- Daniel, you're up.

15:40.439 --> 15:42.859
<i>♪ ♪</i>

15:42.859 --> 15:46.028
<i>- Right off, the shape of the</i>
<i>blade kind of is an issue.</i>

15:46.028 --> 15:47.488
<i>But you got plenty of ricasso.</i>

15:47.488 --> 15:50.116
It's on the lean side,

15:50.116 --> 15:51.617
you know, to continue
grinding on this,

15:51.617 --> 15:53.244
so I'd be careful on

15:53.244 --> 15:54.704
losing more material
out of the center of this

15:54.704 --> 15:56.164
if you move forward.

15:56.164 --> 15:57.707
- Your steel looks good.

15:57.707 --> 16:00.334
But you've got quite
a warp in here.

16:00.334 --> 16:01.752
<i>That can be corrected.</i>

16:01.752 --> 16:03.629
And this really isn't a

16:03.629 --> 16:05.548
European dagger profile
right now,

16:05.548 --> 16:08.718
<i>it's actually a leaf-shaped</i>
<i>dagger profile.</i>

16:08.718 --> 16:10.178
- All right, Drew,

16:10.178 --> 16:11.846
please present your work
to the judges.

16:11.846 --> 16:13.097
<i>♪ ♪</i>

16:13.097 --> 16:14.891
<i>- You know, Drew,</i>

16:14.891 --> 16:16.517
<i>watching somebody work</i>
<i>as well as you did</i>

16:16.517 --> 16:18.561
<i>at half of my age</i>
<i>really impresses me.</i>

16:18.561 --> 16:20.646
Your steel looks
good and tight.

16:20.646 --> 16:23.399
But you do have quite a warp.

16:23.399 --> 16:24.942
<i>There's a few different ways</i>

16:24.942 --> 16:26.402
that you can go ahead
and fix that.

16:26.402 --> 16:28.863
But overall,
a very nice job.

16:28.863 --> 16:30.156
- Thank you.

16:30.156 --> 16:31.616
- All right so,
Drew, first off,

16:31.616 --> 16:32.867
if you're gonna
grind in a vest,

16:32.867 --> 16:34.410
make sure it's 100% cotton,

16:34.410 --> 16:36.412
that thing could
go up in flames.

16:36.412 --> 16:38.247
I really like
the shape of this.

16:38.247 --> 16:40.416
The fact that your
ricasso sets in--

16:40.416 --> 16:42.335
you just have enough
ricasso there.

16:42.335 --> 16:44.921
The lines are really clean.

16:44.921 --> 16:46.380
<i>I like the fact that</i>
<i>that spine</i>

16:46.380 --> 16:47.924
<i>goes all the way to the tip.</i>

16:47.924 --> 16:50.218
Nicely done,
I'm impressed by your work.

16:50.218 --> 16:52.220
- All right, Larry, you're up.

16:52.220 --> 16:54.472
<i>♪ ♪</i>

16:54.472 --> 16:56.766
<i>- Well, Larry,</i>
<i>your steel looks pretty nice,</i>

16:56.766 --> 16:58.559
<i>but we got a few</i>
<i>different issues here.</i>

16:58.559 --> 17:02.521
You're really thin down here
and thicker up here,

17:02.521 --> 17:04.815
<i>and you got quite a wave</i>
<i>in your blade as well.</i>

17:04.815 --> 17:07.610
Big thing,
where's your ricasso?

17:07.610 --> 17:09.987
- I got behind the 8 ball,
ran out of time.

17:09.987 --> 17:12.698
- All right, well, that's--
that's a problem.

17:12.698 --> 17:14.659
- Yeah.

17:14.659 --> 17:18.079
- Larry, your blade was
required to have a ricasso.

17:18.079 --> 17:19.705
It doesn't.

17:19.705 --> 17:20.665
That's grounds for
immediate dismissal

17:20.665 --> 17:21.666
from this forge.

17:21.666 --> 17:23.000
For that reason,

17:23.000 --> 17:25.002
I have to ask you
to please leave.

17:25.002 --> 17:28.422
- I failed to meet one of the
requirements of the ricasso,

17:28.422 --> 17:30.841
<i>but I proved to myself</i>
<i>that I can do this.</i>

17:30.841 --> 17:32.468
<i>It was a lot of fun.</i>

17:32.468 --> 17:35.680
At 61, hey, I don't
think I did that bad.

17:35.680 --> 17:37.890
<i>Somebody's gotta</i>
<i>be going home.</i>

17:37.890 --> 17:40.768
I just was really
wishing it wasn't me.

17:40.768 --> 17:43.271
<i>♪ ♪</i>

17:43.271 --> 17:45.398
- All right, bladesmiths,
congratulations,

17:45.398 --> 17:47.316
you've made it to the second
round of this competition

17:47.316 --> 17:49.026
and now that your blades
have been tempered,

17:49.026 --> 17:50.820
it's time to turn them into
fully functional weapons

17:50.820 --> 17:52.738
by attaching handles to them.

17:52.738 --> 17:56.200
Now, there are some additional
parameters for round two.

17:56.200 --> 17:58.661
In this round,
on your European dagger,

17:58.661 --> 18:00.788
you will have to include
a fluted handle

18:00.788 --> 18:02.665
with at least four flutes,

18:02.665 --> 18:04.959
a double quillon upswept guard,

18:04.959 --> 18:06.752
and a pommel.

18:06.752 --> 18:08.546
You'll have three hours
to complete this.

18:08.546 --> 18:09.714
Good luck, gentlemen.

18:09.714 --> 18:11.966
Your three hours starts now.

18:11.966 --> 18:14.260
<i>[rock music]</i>

18:14.260 --> 18:17.888
Easily our most
parameter-heavy blade

18:17.888 --> 18:20.474
we've ever had as a qualifier.

18:20.474 --> 18:22.101
And then here we are
in round two--

18:22.101 --> 18:23.936
you have to have
a fluted handle,

18:23.936 --> 18:26.022
you have to have
a double quillon guard,

18:26.022 --> 18:28.149
and you have to have a pommel.

18:28.149 --> 18:29.984
That's a lot of stuff.

18:29.984 --> 18:33.904
Kinda makes you wonder what
the finale weapon's gonna be.

18:33.904 --> 18:36.115
- I'm quite nervous.
I got a lot of things to fix.

18:36.115 --> 18:38.451
<i>The judges pointed out</i>
<i>that my blade was</i>

18:38.451 --> 18:40.953
more of a leaf shape
instead of European dagger.

18:40.953 --> 18:43.164
<i>And I'm gonna try</i>
<i>to get the warp out of it,</i>

18:43.164 --> 18:45.291
<i>get my grinds right.</i>

18:45.291 --> 18:48.461
I still have no idea how
I'm going to do these flutes.

18:48.461 --> 18:51.213
<i>I've never even tried one.</i>

18:51.213 --> 18:53.424
- What does that mean, J.?
A fluted handle?

18:53.424 --> 18:56.302
- Flutes are the channels
that are spiraling down

18:56.302 --> 18:57.762
from the pommel to the guard.

18:57.762 --> 18:59.680
Gives you a nice, good grip.

18:59.680 --> 19:01.682
<i>You gotta figure out how</i>
<i>many grooves you wanna do,</i>

19:01.682 --> 19:03.809
<i>how far you're</i>
<i>gonna cut them in.</i>

19:03.809 --> 19:05.853
<i>You also have to plan out</i>
<i>how many times those flutes</i>

19:05.853 --> 19:07.355
<i>are gonna twist</i>
<i>around the handle.</i>

19:07.355 --> 19:09.106
<i>And it has to be symmetrical.</i>

19:09.106 --> 19:12.443
- So I thought flutes
were a musical instrument.

19:12.443 --> 19:14.236
<i>♪ ♪</i>

19:14.236 --> 19:17.531
- So Jason's just grinding out
that tang a little bit.

19:17.531 --> 19:21.577
- The judges mentioned
my blade had a twist to it

19:21.577 --> 19:24.372
<i>and that it was still thick.</i>

19:24.372 --> 19:26.248
So, I'm gonna have to
spend a little bit of time

19:26.248 --> 19:28.209
on the grinder.

19:28.209 --> 19:30.211
My biggest concern

19:30.211 --> 19:31.962
is just getting this handle on.

19:31.962 --> 19:34.423
<i>I generally take a lot</i>
<i>of time to do handles,</i>

19:34.423 --> 19:36.133
<i>so I'm kinda worried</i>

19:36.133 --> 19:38.094
about the time constraints.

19:38.094 --> 19:39.970
<i>♪ ♪</i>

19:39.970 --> 19:41.806
<i>- Now that I've</i>
<i>gotten into round two,</i>

19:41.806 --> 19:44.100
<i>I get to prove what</i>
<i>I'm really made of.</i>

19:44.100 --> 19:45.309
This round is about
what I'm good at--

19:45.309 --> 19:47.103
fit and finish.

19:47.103 --> 19:48.604
<i>I need to straighten</i>
<i>out my blade.</i>

19:48.604 --> 19:50.439
J. Neilson told me that

19:50.439 --> 19:52.066
<i>right at the beginning</i>
<i>of the critiquing.</i>

19:52.066 --> 19:54.026
- Drew's gonna try
and take that warp out,

19:54.026 --> 19:55.820
with a c-clamp
and a couple spacers.

19:55.820 --> 19:58.906
<i>♪ ♪</i>

19:58.906 --> 20:00.741
- And you'll notice the guard
that Daniel's doing--

20:00.741 --> 20:01.826
it's upside down.

20:01.826 --> 20:04.370
- And he's soldered it on.

20:04.370 --> 20:06.497
- He's taking the time
to step back and looking at it.

20:06.497 --> 20:11.711
<i>♪ ♪</i>

20:11.711 --> 20:13.546
- And he's not catching it.

20:13.546 --> 20:15.673
- Somebody needs
to let him know.

20:15.673 --> 20:17.174
- Or he needs to figure it out.

20:17.174 --> 20:19.802
<i>♪ ♪</i>

20:19.802 --> 20:21.053
- [chuckling]

20:21.053 --> 20:22.513
- Daniel just realized
what he did.

20:22.513 --> 20:24.098
- Turn a frown upside down.

20:24.098 --> 20:26.475
- [laughs]

20:26.475 --> 20:29.019
- That definitely would've
been a disqualifier.

20:29.019 --> 20:31.021
<i>That was pretty close.</i>

20:31.021 --> 20:34.191
[applause]
- Phew.

20:34.191 --> 20:36.068
<i>♪ ♪</i>

20:36.068 --> 20:38.279
- Got this grand scheme
in my head for the handle.

20:38.279 --> 20:40.156
I prefer to have
something brass

20:40.156 --> 20:41.907
for the guard and the pommel,

20:41.907 --> 20:43.617
Good.

20:43.617 --> 20:47.538
Putting a slot in a guard
is just meticulous.

20:47.538 --> 20:49.540
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

20:49.540 --> 20:52.084
- What do we got going?

20:52.084 --> 20:54.545
I'm burning up
the angle grinder.

20:54.545 --> 20:57.214
<i>I thought I'd just peel</i>
<i>this piece of brass off.</i>

20:57.214 --> 20:59.216
And I've got a knife.

21:01.510 --> 21:03.637
<i>Knives are not pry bars.</i>

21:03.637 --> 21:05.389
You shouldn't use them
as pry bars.

21:05.389 --> 21:07.933
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

21:07.933 --> 21:10.978
- Oh, whoa, whoa, whoa.

21:10.978 --> 21:12.938
[metallic clang]

21:12.938 --> 21:15.983
[all talking at once]

21:15.983 --> 21:17.359
- Did you guys see that?

21:17.359 --> 21:19.403
<i>♪ ♪</i>

21:19.403 --> 21:21.155
- [laughing]
Oh, my God.

21:21.155 --> 21:23.991
My tip's gone--that's kind
of a big part of a knife.

21:23.991 --> 21:26.786
'Cause that would've
broken off in an oil stab.

21:26.786 --> 21:29.663
That's not gonna fly.
I gotta fix this.

21:29.663 --> 21:31.207
- Bladesmiths!

21:31.207 --> 21:33.959
90 minutes has elapsed!

21:33.959 --> 21:35.252
[laughter]

21:35.252 --> 21:37.046
- Wow.

21:37.046 --> 21:39.423
That's pretty dang good
for freehanding that.

21:39.423 --> 21:40.883
<i>♪ ♪</i>

21:40.883 --> 21:43.052
This handle is pretty chunky.

21:43.052 --> 21:44.512
<i>♪ ♪</i>

21:44.512 --> 21:46.096
I don't have a lot of time.

21:46.096 --> 21:47.515
<i>It's gonna have</i>
<i>to stay pretty big.</i>

21:47.515 --> 21:48.557
[sigh]

21:48.557 --> 21:50.434
<i>I've got epoxy</i>

21:50.434 --> 21:52.269
<i>absolutely everywhere.</i>

21:52.269 --> 21:53.938
That's what I wanna see.

21:53.938 --> 21:55.856
I may even have epoxy

21:55.856 --> 21:57.399
in my underbritches.

21:57.399 --> 21:59.318
<i>♪ ♪</i>

21:59.318 --> 22:01.237
- With the time
that I've got left,

22:01.237 --> 22:03.405
I've gotta get my butt in gear,
get this handle shaped.

22:03.405 --> 22:07.660
I know that flutes have
a round concave profile,

22:07.660 --> 22:11.413
<i>so I just guesstimate</i>
<i>their size.</i>

22:11.413 --> 22:13.874
I'm drilling two different
holes in both ends,

22:13.874 --> 22:15.501
trying to make them
meet in the middle,

22:15.501 --> 22:19.463
and hopefully not burst
through one of my flutes.

22:19.463 --> 22:21.048
- He goes sideways
through that thing,

22:21.048 --> 22:22.591
he's gonna hit his hand.

22:22.591 --> 22:23.801
- Eh, he'll be all right.
- All right.

22:23.801 --> 22:25.344
<i>♪ ♪</i>

22:25.344 --> 22:27.596
- Hey! That worked!

22:27.596 --> 22:30.182
- That's--
goes all the way through.

22:30.182 --> 22:31.725
- Oh, this is a train wreck.

22:31.725 --> 22:32.977
[weakly]
I love what I do.

22:32.977 --> 22:35.896
<i>♪ ♪</i>

22:35.896 --> 22:37.273
- Is Daniel trying
to put flutes in

22:37.273 --> 22:39.149
with the angle grinder?
- Yeah.

22:39.149 --> 22:41.861
- That looks terrifying.

22:41.861 --> 22:44.029
- To me, this handle
is feeling all right.

22:44.029 --> 22:47.241
But I still got
a lot of grinding left.

22:47.241 --> 22:49.577
- Ugh,
Daniel's scaring me, man.

22:49.577 --> 22:51.370
- Hate to see that handle
crack right now.

22:51.370 --> 22:52.413
- That would stink.

22:52.413 --> 22:53.956
<i>♪ ♪</i>

22:53.956 --> 22:56.041
[laughs]
I don't know if I can fix that.

22:56.041 --> 22:57.418
[bleep].

22:57.418 --> 22:59.044
- Oh, boy.

22:59.044 --> 23:00.671
<i>- I get a hole in the handle</i>

23:00.671 --> 23:03.007
all the way down
to where the tang is.

23:03.007 --> 23:05.968
<i>It's a hell of</i>
<i>a aesthetic problem.</i>

23:05.968 --> 23:08.053
<i>I ain't got time to fix this.</i>

23:08.053 --> 23:09.555
I'm gonna go ahead
and work on my blade.

23:09.555 --> 23:12.766
<i>♪ ♪</i>

23:12.766 --> 23:15.811
- Five, four, three,

23:15.811 --> 23:17.688
two, one.

23:17.688 --> 23:19.440
Bladesmiths,
stop what you're doing,

23:19.440 --> 23:22.610
drop your tools,
this round is over.

23:22.610 --> 23:25.154
- I have had one
hell of a round.

23:25.154 --> 23:27.239
<i>I really hope</i>
<i>my blade does well.</i>

23:27.239 --> 23:28.657
<i>It's uglier than sin,</i>

23:28.657 --> 23:31.076
but I know it'll do its job.

23:31.076 --> 23:34.413
- All right, smiths,
welcome to our strength test.

23:34.413 --> 23:36.874
Now, what I'm gonna do is take
each of your daggers

23:36.874 --> 23:40.711
and very violently stab them
into these steel fuel cans.

23:40.711 --> 23:43.255
I don't really care what
your daggers do to the cans.

23:43.255 --> 23:45.466
I wanna see what the cans
are gonna do to your daggers.

23:45.466 --> 23:47.426
Jason, you're up first.
You ready?

23:47.426 --> 23:48.469
- Let's get to it.

23:48.469 --> 23:50.012
- Damn right.

23:50.012 --> 23:52.056
<i>[tense music]</i>

23:52.056 --> 23:54.099
<i>- I'm probably more nervous</i>

23:54.099 --> 23:55.893
<i>than I've ever been</i>
<i>in my life.</i>

23:55.893 --> 23:57.353
<i>Please, please,</i>

23:57.353 --> 24:00.689
let this thing not break.

24:00.689 --> 24:03.734
<i>[rock music]</i>

24:03.734 --> 24:04.944
- [grunts]

24:04.944 --> 24:09.615
<i>♪ ♪</i>

24:09.615 --> 24:11.075
Jason, big thing is,

24:11.075 --> 24:13.994
you picked up a bend
in your blade.

24:13.994 --> 24:16.246
The handle is also very large.

24:16.246 --> 24:17.748
It's kinda hard to hold onto.

24:17.748 --> 24:19.625
And even with the glove
thrusting in,

24:19.625 --> 24:21.168
I could feel those edges.

24:21.168 --> 24:22.753
But overall, you survived.

24:22.753 --> 24:24.338
Good job.
- Thank you.

24:24.338 --> 24:26.131
- Daniel, what are you
thinking? You ready?

24:26.131 --> 24:27.424
- Go for it.

24:27.424 --> 24:28.842
<i>[tense music]</i>

24:28.842 --> 24:30.552
<i>I'm freaking out.</i>

24:30.552 --> 24:32.262
<i>I already seen what</i>
<i>he did to Jason's.</i>

24:32.262 --> 24:34.348
<i>I'm hoping I don't</i>
<i>pick up a warp.</i>

24:34.348 --> 24:36.100
And I hope my handle
doesn't break.

24:36.100 --> 24:38.936
<i>♪ ♪</i>

24:38.936 --> 24:41.981
<i>[rock music]</i>

24:41.981 --> 24:47.653
<i>♪ ♪</i>

24:48.696 --> 24:50.155
- All right, Daniel,

24:50.155 --> 24:52.032
we got a couple problems here.

24:52.032 --> 24:55.244
Your blade and your dagger
picked up a bent.

24:55.244 --> 24:57.246
<i>♪ ♪</i>

24:57.246 --> 24:58.831
And also,
there's a lot of chipping

24:58.831 --> 25:01.291
on both sides of the knife.

25:01.291 --> 25:02.876
And the other thing--
your handle

25:02.876 --> 25:04.837
is very, very lean,

25:04.837 --> 25:06.755
very little to hold onto,

25:06.755 --> 25:09.008
but overall,
your dagger survived.

25:09.008 --> 25:10.884
Good job.
- Thank you.

25:10.884 --> 25:13.429
- Drew, what're you thinking?

25:13.429 --> 25:15.222
- Let's make some holes.

25:15.222 --> 25:16.640
- Let's do that.

25:16.640 --> 25:18.392
<i>[tense music]</i>

25:18.392 --> 25:19.810
<i>- I start quivering</i>
<i>in my boots a little bit</i>

25:19.810 --> 25:21.520
<i>when J. picks up</i>
<i>the blade because</i>

25:21.520 --> 25:23.313
<i>he's got this</i>
<i>look of excitement</i>

25:23.313 --> 25:25.566
<i>and he likes to break things.</i>

25:25.566 --> 25:28.569
<i>[rock music]</i>

25:28.569 --> 25:32.906
<i>♪ ♪</i>

25:32.906 --> 25:33.907
[oil trickling]

25:35.993 --> 25:37.745
- All right, Drew,

25:37.745 --> 25:41.540
you did get a little bit
of a roll on your tip.

25:41.540 --> 25:45.335
And you picked up
a little chip right there.

25:45.335 --> 25:48.589
Your handle is really slim.

25:48.589 --> 25:50.507
And the fluting
doesn't even make

25:50.507 --> 25:52.092
a quarter rotation,
really.

25:52.092 --> 25:54.636
So it's really just ridges
I'm holding onto,

25:54.636 --> 25:56.805
it's not the most comfortable
handle in the world.

25:56.805 --> 25:59.058
But overall, your dagger
survived, good job.

25:59.058 --> 26:00.684
- Thank you.

26:00.684 --> 26:02.770
<i>♪ ♪</i>

26:02.770 --> 26:05.522
- Bladesmiths, to see
how sharp your blades are,

26:05.522 --> 26:07.107
I will stab this fish.

26:07.107 --> 26:08.942
I will slice this fish.

26:08.942 --> 26:10.319
Unlike the strength test,

26:10.319 --> 26:11.862
this is all about
what your knife

26:11.862 --> 26:13.489
will do to the fish.

26:13.489 --> 26:15.532
Jason, you're up first,
you ready for this?

26:15.532 --> 26:17.284
- Let's go.

26:17.284 --> 26:20.454
<i>I know it's sharp,</i>
<i>but I picked up a bend</i>

26:20.454 --> 26:22.790
which may really
affect the cutting test,

26:22.790 --> 26:25.375
<i>so I'm actually</i>
<i>checking my heart.</i>

26:25.375 --> 26:27.002
<i>[laughing]</i>
<i>Counting the beats,</i>

26:27.002 --> 26:29.213
thinking I might be
having a heart attack.

26:29.213 --> 26:30.546
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

26:32.841 --> 26:35.761
<i>[rock music]</i>

26:35.761 --> 26:42.851
<i>♪ ♪</i>

26:44.478 --> 26:46.230
- All right, Jason, let's talk
about your dagger right here.

26:46.230 --> 26:48.565
First up, your inside edge.

26:48.565 --> 26:50.609
Once you penetrate
into the fish,

26:50.609 --> 26:53.946
your edge is sharp
enough to slash off.

26:53.946 --> 26:58.200
Now, in a motion where you're
slashing away from the fish,

26:58.200 --> 27:00.619
this edge cut cleanly
on the bottom,

27:00.619 --> 27:03.205
but the other cuts pretty much
bounced off the fish.

27:03.205 --> 27:05.499
But overall, it will cut.

27:05.499 --> 27:06.959
- Thank you.

27:06.959 --> 27:08.252
- Daniel, you're up next,
you ready?

27:08.252 --> 27:09.294
- Let's make sushi.

27:09.294 --> 27:10.254
- Absolutely.

27:12.464 --> 27:19.429
<i>♪ ♪</i>

27:22.808 --> 27:25.143
All right, Daniel,
let's talk about your blade.

27:25.143 --> 27:26.520
One of your edges cuts clean.

27:26.520 --> 27:27.813
When you penetrate
into the fish,

27:27.813 --> 27:29.565
lacerates all the way.

27:29.565 --> 27:32.067
But the area that has
a little bit of a chip

27:32.067 --> 27:35.529
does show a little bit of some
jagged cuts over the fish.

27:35.529 --> 27:37.906
But the important thing
is it will cut.

27:37.906 --> 27:39.116
- Thank you.

27:39.116 --> 27:40.409
- All right, Drew, you ready?

27:40.409 --> 27:41.660
- Let's do this.

27:41.660 --> 27:43.370
This is making me feel nervous.

27:43.370 --> 27:45.372
<i>But all I have to do</i>

27:45.372 --> 27:47.833
<i>is make sure I outperform</i>
<i>Jason at this point.</i>

27:47.833 --> 27:54.673
<i>♪ ♪</i>

28:00.137 --> 28:01.638
- Well, young man,

28:01.638 --> 28:04.516
your dagger has a
great symmetry in here

28:04.516 --> 28:06.226
that it penetrates
deep for the thrust

28:06.226 --> 28:09.396
and lacerates cleanly
on your drag coming down.

28:09.396 --> 28:11.481
The big issue is your handle.

28:11.481 --> 28:13.150
It's on the slim side

28:13.150 --> 28:16.069
and your fluting did not
provide a very good grip,

28:16.069 --> 28:18.030
so it started to
rotate a little bit,

28:18.030 --> 28:19.406
especially because
of all the slimage

28:19.406 --> 28:20.490
you're getting
from the fish.

28:20.490 --> 28:23.201
But your edges will cut.

28:23.201 --> 28:25.787
- That's all I needed to hear.

28:25.787 --> 28:28.707
- Bladesmiths, the judges have
completed their deliberation.

28:28.707 --> 28:30.334
They've made a final decision.

28:30.334 --> 28:32.544
It's time for one of you
to leave The Forge.

28:32.544 --> 28:35.589
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

28:35.589 --> 28:38.425
Daniel,
your blade didn't make the cut.

28:38.425 --> 28:40.302
- Daniel,
during the strength test,

28:40.302 --> 28:43.722
you lost chunks of your edge
on both sides of the dagger.

28:43.722 --> 28:45.599
<i>And you had a failure</i>
<i>on the handle too--</i>

28:45.599 --> 28:47.351
<i>that hole that's</i>
<i>punched through</i>

28:47.351 --> 28:49.227
<i>into where the tang</i>
<i>is sitting.</i>

28:49.227 --> 28:51.563
That's why we're
gonna let you go.

28:51.563 --> 28:54.816
- Daniel,
please surrender your blade.

28:54.816 --> 28:56.985
<i>- I agree with</i>
<i>the judges' decisions.</i>

28:56.985 --> 28:59.738
The chips in the handle were
just too much to get past.

28:59.738 --> 29:01.323
<i>I had a heck of a good time.</i>

29:01.323 --> 29:03.742
It was a great
personal accomplishment.

29:03.742 --> 29:05.369
<i>When I get home to Missouri,</i>

29:05.369 --> 29:07.621
<i>I'm gonna spend</i>
<i>some time with my wife</i>

29:07.621 --> 29:09.831
and then get right back
to smithing.

29:09.831 --> 29:12.250
<i>♪ ♪</i>

29:12.250 --> 29:14.378
- Jason, Drew,
congratulations,

29:14.378 --> 29:16.964
you guys made it into the final
round of this competition.

29:16.964 --> 29:18.507
Now we're sending you back
to your home forges

29:18.507 --> 29:20.717
to recreate an iconic weapon
from history.

29:20.717 --> 29:22.219
That weapon is...

29:22.219 --> 29:25.389
<i>♪ ♪</i>

29:25.389 --> 29:27.140
The Zande spear.

29:27.140 --> 29:28.809
- Ooh, boy.

29:28.809 --> 29:30.644
<i>- One of the</i>
<i>deadliest weapons used</i>

29:30.644 --> 29:32.646
<i>by the Zande tribes</i>
<i>of Central Africa,</i>

29:32.646 --> 29:34.439
<i>the Zande spear was</i>
<i>used for fighting</i>

29:34.439 --> 29:36.233
<i>as well as for hunting.</i>

29:36.233 --> 29:38.276
<i>Known throughout history</i>
<i>as conquering warriors,</i>

29:38.276 --> 29:40.445
<i>the Zande exhibited</i>
<i>unmatched skills</i>

29:40.445 --> 29:41.905
<i>on the battlefield.</i>

29:41.905 --> 29:43.573
<i>Fixed to</i>
<i>a wooden shaft,</i>

29:43.573 --> 29:45.033
<i>the spear was suitable</i>
<i>for throwing</i>

29:45.033 --> 29:47.119
<i>and attacking from</i>
<i>long distances,</i>

29:47.119 --> 29:49.204
<i>but its thrusting ability</i>
<i>made it just as effective</i>

29:49.204 --> 29:51.289
<i>as a close combat weapon.</i>

29:51.289 --> 29:53.667
<i>The sharp upper and lower</i>
<i>tines and multiple spikes</i>

29:53.667 --> 29:56.336
<i>inflicted deadly wounds</i>
<i>both upon entry and exit</i>

29:56.336 --> 29:58.088
<i>from the victim's body.</i>

29:58.088 --> 30:00.549
<i>The Zande's lethal use</i>
<i>of the spear can be seen</i>

30:00.549 --> 30:04.511
<i>highlighted in the game,</i>
<i>"Deadliest Warrior."</i>

30:04.511 --> 30:06.013
The weapons themselves

30:06.013 --> 30:08.015
must fall within the
following parameters.

30:08.015 --> 30:10.434
Your spearhead
must include tines

30:10.434 --> 30:12.686
that are at least
three inches long.

30:12.686 --> 30:15.480
Your Zande spear
must include a shaft.

30:15.480 --> 30:18.483
Your shaft must be at least
1 1/2 inches

30:18.483 --> 30:21.194
in diameter, and have
a circular cross section.

30:21.194 --> 30:23.697
<i>- It's certainly</i>
<i>gonna be a challenge</i>

30:23.697 --> 30:26.616
but I know I can rise
to this challenge.

30:26.616 --> 30:28.410
- You will have five days
at your home forge

30:28.410 --> 30:29.786
to complete this challenge.

30:29.786 --> 30:31.788
After five days,
you will return

30:31.788 --> 30:33.999
and present your weapons
to our judges.

30:33.999 --> 30:36.084
After they've tested
and inspected them,

30:36.084 --> 30:38.712
they will declare one of you
the "Forged in Fire" champion

30:38.712 --> 30:41.131
and hand you a check
for 10 grand.

30:41.131 --> 30:43.633
Good luck.
We'll see you in five days.

30:43.633 --> 30:45.260
<i>[rock music]</i>

30:45.260 --> 30:47.637
<i>- It's day one,</i>
<i>and all I wanna do today</i>

30:47.637 --> 30:49.598
<i>is get the blade forged out.</i>

30:49.598 --> 30:52.392
So I've got a
piece of 1084 steel.

30:52.392 --> 30:54.603
<i>It's not quite enough</i>
<i>for what I want to do,</i>

30:54.603 --> 30:56.313
I'm gonna have to do
some creative thinking

30:56.313 --> 30:57.939
to make it work.

30:57.939 --> 31:00.525
I've taken that
20-inch piece of steel

31:00.525 --> 31:03.403
and just by doing that much,

31:03.403 --> 31:06.448
drawn it to over 21 inches.
[metal clanging]

31:06.448 --> 31:08.742
I wanna get the spearhead
completely forged today.

31:08.742 --> 31:13.497
Got marks where I'm gonna
cut into and stop.

31:13.497 --> 31:15.665
I'm gonna bend those out
and draw them back.

31:15.665 --> 31:17.334
That's a good plan.

31:17.334 --> 31:20.378
<i>♪ ♪</i>

31:20.378 --> 31:22.589
<i>- I'm here back</i>
<i>in my home forge.</i>

31:22.589 --> 31:25.634
<i>What we're making is</i>
<i>a Zande warrior spear.</i>

31:25.634 --> 31:28.095
This thing is vicious.

31:28.095 --> 31:32.349
<i>We're gonna establish</i>
<i>the point first,</i>

31:32.349 --> 31:35.727
and work our way
on back to the tang.

31:35.727 --> 31:40.273
<i>These tines need to get</i>
<i>drawn out to three inches.</i>

31:40.273 --> 31:44.319
That is not what I wanna see.

31:44.319 --> 31:46.613
It's looking like I got
inch and a half,

31:46.613 --> 31:48.365
maybe two inches.

31:48.365 --> 31:50.283
What am I gonna do?

31:50.283 --> 31:52.494
<i>Here I am seven hours</i>
<i>into day one</i>

31:52.494 --> 31:55.664
and I'm realizing this
just isn't gonna work.

31:55.664 --> 31:57.666
<i>I just don't have</i>
<i>the material here.</i>

31:57.666 --> 32:00.710
<i>I forged this thing</i>
<i>way too short.</i>

32:00.710 --> 32:02.420
Damn, that's--

32:02.420 --> 32:04.005
<i>- First thing today--</i>

32:04.005 --> 32:06.091
I'm gonna forge weld
two pieces of steel

32:06.091 --> 32:07.717
on either end of this

32:07.717 --> 32:09.469
'cause it's getting thin

32:09.469 --> 32:11.805
and I don't want this
to bend in the slightest.

32:11.805 --> 32:14.724
I know in the testing they're
going to abuse my weapon,

32:14.724 --> 32:15.934
<i>but I'm not worried about it,</i>

32:15.934 --> 32:17.602
<i>because I know what I'm doing.</i>

32:17.602 --> 32:19.020
<i>♪ ♪</i>

32:19.020 --> 32:20.647
[dry laugh]
Ow.

32:20.647 --> 32:22.607
Way to ding myself in the head.

32:22.607 --> 32:23.817
Oww.

32:23.817 --> 32:24.985
[machine whirring]

32:24.985 --> 32:29.030
Three, two, one.

32:29.030 --> 32:31.408
<i>♪ ♪</i>

32:31.408 --> 32:33.952
<i>I'm sitting here waiting</i>
<i>for a ping or a pop</i>

32:33.952 --> 32:35.704
<i>or something scraping.</i>

32:35.704 --> 32:36.913
<i>But I don't hear it.</i>

32:36.913 --> 32:38.665
Just a nice little sizzle.

32:38.665 --> 32:42.294
<i>♪ ♪</i>

32:42.294 --> 32:43.461
[metal clanging]

32:43.461 --> 32:45.380
Oh, God.

32:48.383 --> 32:50.260
Just lost part of my time.

32:50.260 --> 32:52.012
I've gotta figure out
something to do.

32:52.012 --> 32:54.264
<i>This is not gonna</i>
<i>make the requirements,</i>

32:54.264 --> 32:56.183
<i>so I'm just gonna</i>
<i>toss this out</i>

32:56.183 --> 32:57.350
<i>and grab a new</i>
<i>piece of steel.</i>

32:57.350 --> 32:58.518
<i>Making another blade.</i>

32:58.518 --> 33:00.687
<i>♪ ♪</i>

33:00.687 --> 33:03.273
I've got three hours
to get this done

33:03.273 --> 33:05.942
<i>and I've just gotta get at it.</i>

33:05.942 --> 33:07.944
So I've done this,
I'm gonna cut in,

33:07.944 --> 33:10.488
stick it in the forge,
and spread those out.

33:10.488 --> 33:11.781
[clang]

33:11.781 --> 33:14.326
Good plan, good plan.

33:14.326 --> 33:16.328
<i>♪ ♪</i>

33:16.328 --> 33:18.288
<i>- Here we are at the</i>
<i>beginning of day three.</i>

33:18.288 --> 33:20.790
<i>I'm feeling a bit of a crunch,</i>

33:20.790 --> 33:24.419
but I think I've kinda gotten
myself back on schedule.

33:24.419 --> 33:26.129
I'm ready for the quench.

33:26.129 --> 33:28.006
<i>Nervous as hell.</i>

33:28.006 --> 33:30.842
<i>99% of the time,</i>
<i>if you're gonna lose a blade,</i>

33:30.842 --> 33:32.802
<i>you're gonna lose it</i>
<i>during the quench.</i>

33:32.802 --> 33:35.764
<i>I'm at a point where</i>
<i>I just don't have time</i>

33:35.764 --> 33:37.432
<i>to reforge this thing again,</i>

33:37.432 --> 33:39.476
so it's a make or break moment.

33:39.476 --> 33:42.312
<i>[tense music]</i>

33:42.312 --> 33:44.648
There's no cracks,
nothing I can see.

33:44.648 --> 33:47.609
<i>Everything still</i>
<i>stays straight.</i>

33:47.609 --> 33:50.070
That's hard.

33:50.070 --> 33:52.864
<i>- My blade is</i>
<i>basically finished</i>

33:52.864 --> 33:54.950
<i>and I've allotted</i>
<i>the entire day</i>

33:54.950 --> 33:57.369
<i>to finishing the shaft</i>
<i>of the spear.</i>

33:57.369 --> 34:00.538
<i>Fitting, sharpening,</i>
<i>nothing big.</i>

34:00.538 --> 34:02.540
The tang doesn't quite
fit in the shaft.

34:02.540 --> 34:05.043
<i>♪ ♪</i>

34:05.043 --> 34:06.878
Why? Why is this happening?

34:06.878 --> 34:08.964
<i>I'm almost over the</i>
<i>height requirement.</i>

34:08.964 --> 34:10.590
<i>♪ ♪</i>

34:10.590 --> 34:12.217
Uh, okay.

34:12.217 --> 34:13.510
Crisis averted, I'm all good.

34:13.510 --> 34:15.095
[sighs]

34:15.095 --> 34:17.222
I don't even know
what I feel right now.

34:17.222 --> 34:19.808
[sighing]
Okay.

34:19.808 --> 34:20.809
Let the panic

34:20.809 --> 34:22.936
get--get ov--yep.

34:22.936 --> 34:24.229
Yep.

34:24.229 --> 34:26.189
Gonna chill out.

34:26.189 --> 34:27.315
Okay.

34:27.315 --> 34:28.400
[inhales deeply]

34:28.400 --> 34:30.318
<i>♪ ♪</i>

34:30.318 --> 34:32.737
- Day five here, thank God.

34:32.737 --> 34:36.157
<i>I've got this piece</i>
<i>of square 2x2 ash</i>

34:36.157 --> 34:38.076
<i>that I've gotta turn into</i>

34:38.076 --> 34:41.121
<i>an inch and a half</i>
<i>round piece of ash.</i>

34:41.121 --> 34:43.540
This thing's
coming out by hand.

34:43.540 --> 34:46.626
<i>So I'm just gonna have to</i>
<i>go with my gut on this one</i>

34:46.626 --> 34:48.795
and take the assumption
that the judges

34:48.795 --> 34:52.132
are gonna wanna see
about an inch and a half.

34:52.132 --> 34:54.467
I'm feeling a little
bit more relaxed

34:54.467 --> 34:59.347
than I was at this time
yesterday, that's for sure.

34:59.347 --> 35:01.349
<i>Coming out on top</i>
<i>of this challenge</i>

35:01.349 --> 35:04.394
would be a real game changer
for my fiancée and I.

35:04.394 --> 35:07.063
<i>Drew is a really good friend,</i>

35:07.063 --> 35:10.400
but you know what?
He's going down.

35:10.400 --> 35:13.361
<i>[tense music]</i>

35:13.361 --> 35:15.238
- Drew, Jason,
welcome back to The Forge.

35:15.238 --> 35:16.740
You've had five days
at your home forges

35:16.740 --> 35:18.533
to work on these Zande spears.

35:18.533 --> 35:19.826
Drew, how'd it go for you?

35:19.826 --> 35:21.369
- Aside from having to restart,

35:21.369 --> 35:22.454
it went pretty well.

35:22.454 --> 35:24.706
<i>♪ ♪</i>

35:24.706 --> 35:27.417
<i>Spearhead is just simple</i>
<i>1080 steel from flat stock.</i>

35:27.417 --> 35:29.461
<i>All the barbs</i>
<i>are just bent up</i>

35:29.461 --> 35:31.129
<i>to look as nasty as possible.</i>

35:31.129 --> 35:33.256
- Jason, how'd it go for you?

35:33.256 --> 35:36.259
- You guys definitely invented
blacksmith hell here.

35:36.259 --> 35:38.178
<i>♪ ♪</i>

35:38.178 --> 35:42.599
<i>Mine is forged</i>
<i>from one piece--5160.</i>

35:42.599 --> 35:45.060
<i>And I tried to keep it</i>
<i>as traditional</i>

35:45.060 --> 35:48.063
<i>to the museum examples</i>
<i>as I could find.</i>

35:48.063 --> 35:50.440
- Gentlemen,
your Zande spears look deadly,

35:50.440 --> 35:53.068
so let's find out if they
really are in our weapons test.

35:53.068 --> 35:55.278
Up first, the kill test.

35:55.278 --> 35:57.030
Doug?

35:57.030 --> 35:59.574
- Bladesmiths,
I will take your Zande spears

35:59.574 --> 36:01.951
and deliver killing blows
on this ballistics dummy.

36:01.951 --> 36:04.204
Drew, you're up first,
you ready?

36:04.204 --> 36:06.247
- Let's make those
intestines out-testines.

36:06.247 --> 36:07.582
- [laughs]
All right, let's do that.

36:07.582 --> 36:08.625
I like that.

36:08.625 --> 36:10.168
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

36:10.168 --> 36:11.961
<i>Right now, I'm about</i>
<i>to hear Doug say</i>

36:11.961 --> 36:13.755
<i>"It will kill,"</i>

36:13.755 --> 36:14.798
<i>and that's the only</i>
<i>thing I'm here for.</i>

36:14.798 --> 36:16.508
<i>♪ ♪</i>

36:16.508 --> 36:17.884
- To help me out today,

36:17.884 --> 36:19.969
please welcome back
R. J. Marcaida.

36:19.969 --> 36:22.931
He will have the pleasure
of wielding your Zande spear.

36:22.931 --> 36:25.141
<i>♪ ♪</i>

36:25.141 --> 36:28.103
<i>[rock music]</i>

36:28.103 --> 36:35.068
<i>♪ ♪</i>

36:40.490 --> 36:41.991
[sharp cracking]

36:41.991 --> 36:44.077
- [laughing]
Ooh.

36:44.077 --> 36:46.830
<i>[tense music]</i>

36:46.830 --> 36:49.332
- All right, Drew,
it feels very good in the hand.

36:49.332 --> 36:51.459
It lacerates deep
when we thrust this

36:51.459 --> 36:53.044
into the chest cavity,
into the heart.

36:53.044 --> 36:54.587
On its way out,

36:54.587 --> 36:56.965
not only does it take
some skin with it,

36:56.965 --> 36:59.092
but it also took out some ribs.

36:59.092 --> 37:01.428
Your tines right here,
from the side entry--

37:01.428 --> 37:04.180
the spear went all the way
through and on its way out,

37:04.180 --> 37:06.516
it took everything
that was in its path.

37:06.516 --> 37:08.309
But there is one issue.

37:08.309 --> 37:12.439
As you can see,
your tip right here broke off.

37:12.439 --> 37:13.732
But other than that,

37:13.732 --> 37:15.775
this is a weapon that is deadly

37:15.775 --> 37:17.694
and it will kill.

37:17.694 --> 37:19.320
- Thank you.

37:19.320 --> 37:20.989
- All right, Jason, your turn.
You ready?

37:20.989 --> 37:23.199
- I know it will cut.
[laughs]

37:23.199 --> 37:24.701
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

37:24.701 --> 37:26.828
<i>It bit me four times</i>
<i>making it.</i>

37:26.828 --> 37:30.039
I'm thinking it's going
to wreck this thing's day.

37:30.039 --> 37:32.417
<i>♪ ♪</i>

37:32.417 --> 37:35.295
<i>[rock music]</i>

37:35.295 --> 37:42.218
<i>♪ ♪</i>

37:48.850 --> 37:51.770
<i>[tense music]</i>

37:51.770 --> 37:53.188
- All right, Jason,

37:53.188 --> 37:55.190
the balance of your
weapon feels good.

37:55.190 --> 37:57.525
When it penetrated
into the chest cavity,

37:57.525 --> 37:59.694
it hit a rib and
broke it in half,

37:59.694 --> 38:03.990
got into the heart, and there
was no edge damage on your tip.

38:03.990 --> 38:06.326
All these hooks right here did
what it was supposed to do--

38:06.326 --> 38:08.953
into the abdomen, ripped
everything out, even the barb.

38:08.953 --> 38:11.331
And the beautiful
thing about this is

38:11.331 --> 38:12.832
it will kill.

38:12.832 --> 38:14.793
- That's what I wanted to hear.

38:14.793 --> 38:16.419
<i>♪ ♪</i>

38:16.419 --> 38:18.254
- Say hello to my
little friend here.

38:18.254 --> 38:21.174
<i>[rock music]</i>

38:21.174 --> 38:22.842
Today we're gonna test
the overall strength

38:22.842 --> 38:25.261
and construction of
your Zande spears by--

38:25.261 --> 38:27.222
well, we're gonna fire them
out of this cannon

38:27.222 --> 38:29.140
into this wood block wall.

38:29.140 --> 38:30.558
Now, I'm not concerned about

38:30.558 --> 38:32.143
what your spears
do to the wall,

38:32.143 --> 38:34.729
I wanna see how well your
spears survive the wall.

38:34.729 --> 38:36.314
Drew, you're up first,
you ready?

38:36.314 --> 38:37.690
- No.
[laughs]

38:37.690 --> 38:38.900
- Well,
we're gonna do it anyway.

38:38.900 --> 38:40.485
- Let's do it.

38:40.485 --> 38:42.362
<i>I don't even know</i>
<i>what to think.</i>

38:42.362 --> 38:46.533
I'm scared because this
thing is gonna be launched.

38:46.533 --> 38:49.744
<i>It looks like he's about</i>
<i>to break my spear.</i>

38:49.744 --> 38:50.870
Oh, God...
[laughs]

38:53.581 --> 38:56.543
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

38:56.543 --> 39:03.383
<i>♪ ♪</i>

39:08.888 --> 39:10.890
- That worked really well,
Drew.

39:10.890 --> 39:13.059
Despite the fact that you did
lose a little bit of your tip

39:13.059 --> 39:15.019
in the kill test,

39:15.019 --> 39:17.939
didn't have any effect
going into that block wall.

39:17.939 --> 39:21.317
Matter of fact,
you sunk all the way down here.

39:21.317 --> 39:22.527
Very impressive.

39:22.527 --> 39:23.903
Your shaft is fine,

39:23.903 --> 39:25.697
nothing loosened up,
nothing cracked.

39:25.697 --> 39:27.991
Your spearhead is still solid.

39:27.991 --> 39:31.286
Overall, it survived.
Very good.

39:31.286 --> 39:33.162
- Thank you.

39:33.162 --> 39:34.789
- So, Jason,
what are you thinking?

39:34.789 --> 39:37.125
- I'm thinking
let's make splinters.

39:37.125 --> 39:39.085
<i>♪ ♪</i>

39:39.085 --> 39:40.545
I'm a little bit
worried they're gonna

39:40.545 --> 39:41.963
shoot this thing
at a wall.

39:41.963 --> 39:43.756
<i>and it could break.</i>

39:43.756 --> 39:44.716
We don't want that.

39:44.716 --> 39:49.012
<i>♪ ♪</i>

39:49.012 --> 39:51.306
- That's a problem.

39:51.306 --> 39:53.141
- Oh, God, no.

39:53.141 --> 39:55.768
<i>♪ ♪</i>

39:55.768 --> 39:58.313
<i>I'm seeing it hang up</i>
<i>a bit on the barrel,</i>

39:58.313 --> 40:00.940
and my heart just
absolutely sinks.

40:00.940 --> 40:03.026
[murmuring indistinctly]

40:03.026 --> 40:07.989
<i>[tense music]</i>

40:07.989 --> 40:10.575
- Jason, we've got
a big problem here.

40:10.575 --> 40:12.118
The parameters that we've
set for these weapons

40:12.118 --> 40:14.203
are for testing purposes.

40:14.203 --> 40:16.789
Because your blade didn't meet
the inch and a half parameter

40:16.789 --> 40:18.499
with a circular cross section,

40:18.499 --> 40:21.336
we cannot fit the shaft
of your weapon

40:21.336 --> 40:24.339
down the barrel of our
testing apparatus here.

40:24.339 --> 40:26.090
And because we can't test it

40:26.090 --> 40:28.426
evenly and fairly
with Drew's blade,

40:28.426 --> 40:30.637
I have to ask you to
please leave The Forge.

40:30.637 --> 40:32.764
<i>♪ ♪</i>

40:32.764 --> 40:36.059
- This was absolutely
worse-case scenario.

40:36.059 --> 40:38.937
<i>Neither Drew nor I wanted</i>
<i>to see either of us</i>

40:38.937 --> 40:40.855
<i>going out on</i>
<i>something like this.</i>

40:40.855 --> 40:43.858
I was over those dimensions
100 times,

40:43.858 --> 40:46.069
and apparently
somewhere in there,

40:46.069 --> 40:48.988
there is one little spot
that I missed.

40:48.988 --> 40:51.032
I'm proud that I got this far,

40:51.032 --> 40:53.910
<i>but I'm incredibly</i>
<i>disappointed.</i>

40:53.910 --> 40:56.704
- Well, Drew, in a competition
where attention to detail

40:56.704 --> 40:58.873
is just as critical
as craftsmanship,

40:58.873 --> 41:01.501
you are the
"Forged in Fire" champion

41:01.501 --> 41:03.169
and will be collecting
a check for $10,000.

41:03.169 --> 41:04.379
Good job.

41:04.379 --> 41:06.881
[applause]
- Oh, my God.

41:06.881 --> 41:08.216
Ohh.

41:08.216 --> 41:10.009
- How you feeling right now?

41:10.009 --> 41:11.928
- I'm 18-year-old,

41:11.928 --> 41:13.846
and I'm the
"Forged in Fire" champion,

41:13.846 --> 41:15.598
what, what just happened?

41:15.598 --> 41:17.684
- Well, I think the best
blade just won, my friend.

41:17.684 --> 41:18.726
Come over here
and shake our hands.

41:18.726 --> 41:20.979
- Oh, God.

41:20.979 --> 41:22.730
<i>Didn't wanna win this way,</i>

41:22.730 --> 41:25.692
but I won and that's
kind of all that matters.

41:25.692 --> 41:27.694
<i>I started</i>
<i>bladesmithing seriously</i>

41:27.694 --> 41:29.487
<i>because of this show.</i>

41:29.487 --> 41:33.032
<i>I learned all that I had</i>
<i>to learn to make it here</i>

41:33.032 --> 41:34.742
and I just won.

41:34.742 --> 41:36.995
This--this is the dream.

41:36.995 --> 41:38.955
[laughing]
Oh, my God, man!

41:38.955 --> 41:41.916
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

41:41.916 --> 41:45.211
<i>♪ ♪</i>
